<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880808-0166 </DOCNO><HL> Letters to the Editor: Japan's Patent Rules Impede U.S. Investors </HL><SO> </SO><CO> JAPAN </CO><TEXT>   Re George Melloan's July 12 Business World article &quot;An American Views Japan's Copycat Culture&quot; and the comment that in Japan &quot;it is possible to patent a relatively minor change, 'such as a bicycle with red pedals.'&quot; My experience has been just the opposite: It is difficult for U.S. inventors to patent those things that have been patented in the U.S. and the Japanese examiners use vague and irrelevant prior patents and reasons. It is way past time for us to examine our relationship with Japan, its treatment of U.S. inventors, and our treatment of patent applications sent from Japan or its local companies.    Patrick F. Henry Sr.    Attorney   Atlanta</TEXT></DOC>